1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,921
The best educational environments are those that are fair to all students, male or female.

2
00:00:09,921 --> 00:00:19,607
But in many places around the world, female and male students do not always have the same chances for a good education.

3
00:00:19,607 --> 00:00:26,846
In today’s teaching tips, we will discuss supporting gender equality in the classroom.

4
00:00:26,846 --> 00:00:33,449
We also will discuss how to create a more equal and balanced learning environment.

5
00:00:33,449 --> 00:00:47,919
The United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) says access to a good education is important for getting out of poverty.

6
00:00:47,919 --> 00:00:56,774
An educated individual is more likely to grow up healthy and have more opportunities for employment.

7
00:00:56,774 --> 00:01:04,825
This increases their chance of raising healthy children, and supporting them to also get an education.

8
00:01:04,825 --> 00:01:15,778
When all students, both male and female, have equal access to educational opportunities, the results impact future generations.

9
00:00:00,000 --> 00:01:24,142
Creating more equal educational opportunities for students begins in the classroom and with the teacher.

10
00:01:24,142 --> 00:01:34,063
A strong teacher is one who treats their students fairly and creates an environment where students feel equally able to take part.

11
00:01:34,063 --> 00:01:39,213
1. Tips for learning environments

12
00:01:39,213 --> 00:01:48,289
Teachers can create the appearance of gender bias through unintentional, nonverbal actions.

13
00:01:48,289 --> 00:01:59,388
The first step to correcting this problem is to organize your classroom in a way that makes all students feel equal.

14
00:01:59,388 --> 00:02:02,084
Establish rules

15
00:02:02,084 --> 00:02:11,472
It is important for a teacher to establish a set of rules from the very beginning that promote equality.

16
00:02:11,472 --> 00:02:18,258
An effective way to do this is to create class rules with students.

17
00:02:18,258 --> 00:02:28,066
Ask students to suggest ideas for how to keep an equal and respectful classroom.

18
00:02:28,066 --> 00:02:37,413
This permits the teacher to point to the rules as something that the whole class has agreed on.

19
00:02:37,413 --> 00:02:50,003
It is important to include rules that deal with respecting students, respecting the teacher and participating in class.

20
00:02:50,003 --> 00:02:57,253
Have a classroom seating plan that supports equal participation.

21
00:02:57,253 --> 00:03:12,249
If you find that certain students, regardless of their gender, are not participating in class, try to change your class seating plan.

22
00:03:12,249 --> 00:03:19,693
For example, try having students who usually sit in the back come to the front.

23
00:03:19,693 --> 00:03:26,098
Teachers tend to interact the most with students sitting closest to them.

24
00:03:26,098 --> 00:03:37,856
For this reason, it is important to change the seating order (if possible) to give all students a chance to sit near the teacher.

25
00:03:37,856 --> 00:03:45,206
Have equal academic and behavior expectations for all students.

26
00:03:45,206 --> 00:04:02,170
Teachers should try to avoid making things easier for either male or female students by giving them easier questions in class, or trying to solve things for the students.

27
00:04:02,170 --> 00:04:11,452
Doing this can create the perception that certain students are not as smart as others.

28
00:04:11,452 --> 00:04:17,281
Teachers should hold the same expectations of all students.

29
00:04:17,281 --> 00:04:20,244
Use group work

30
00:04:20,244 --> 00:04:31,296
Often there will be some students, male or female, who are not comfortable speaking in front of large classes.

31
00:04:31,296 --> 00:04:37,464
But, they may feel more comfortable speaking in small groups.

32
00:04:37,464 --> 00:04:50,971
In order to give all students the opportunity to take part in class, try doing some activities in small groups of three to four students.

33
00:04:50,971 --> 00:04:55,921
2. Tips for classroom strategies

34
00:04:55,921 --> 00:05:06,692
After organizing your class in a way that promotes equality, the next step is to consider the effects of your actions in class.

35
00:05:06,692 --> 00:05:10,230
Addressing students equally

36
00:05:10,230 --> 00:05:18,752
One of the main opportunities students have to participate in class is when they are answering teachers’ questions.

37
00:05:18,752 --> 00:05:25,697
Teachers need to call on or talk to both female and male students in a balanced way.

38
00:05:25,697 --> 00:05:35,594
Research shows that both male and female teachers often call on male students to speak in class more often than female students.

39
00:05:35,594 --> 00:05:39,955
Provide enough wait time to answer questions.

40
00:05:39,955 --> 00:05:49,015
Some students, male or female, may need time to think about the answer to a question when called on by a teacher.

41
00:05:49,015 --> 00:05:58,838
When calling on students who seem to wait longer to answer a question, make sure to give students at least four to five seconds.

42
00:05:58,838 --> 00:06:06,377
Research shows that giving students more time to answer will increase the number of students who participate.

43
00:06:06,377 --> 00:06:09,576
Use gender neutral language

44
00:06:09,576 --> 00:06:15,170
Sometimes in English people use male pronouns when referring to a group.

45
00:06:15,170 --> 00:06:19,291
But, this can make female students feel left out.

46
00:06:19,291 --> 00:06:24,853
Teachers should use gender neutral pronouns whenever possible.

47
00:06:24,853 --> 00:06:36,876
One example is, instead of saying “guys” when referring to a class or group (which is common in American English), say “everybody” or “everyone.”

48
00:06:36,876 --> 00:06:38,986
Body language

49
00:06:38,986 --> 00:06:47,131
Teachers may not realize that their body language with female students might be different from what it is with male students.

50
00:06:47,131 --> 00:06:54,015
Whenever male or female students are talking, use respectful, listening body language.

51
00:06:54,015 --> 00:07:00,009
Face the listener, do not walk away, and do not interrupt students.

52
00:07:00,009 --> 00:07:06,167
Also the teacher can move to different areas of the classroom while speaking.

53
00:07:06,167 --> 00:07:12,566
This is important because students sitting further from the teacher tend to participate less.

54
00:07:12,566 --> 00:07:15,001
Discipline

55
00:07:15,001 --> 00:07:24,724
Be aware when male students insult female students, or female students insult male students.

56
00:07:24,724 --> 00:07:35,925
If the insults appear to be gender-based, students may be discouraged from participating in class in the future.

57
00:07:35,925 --> 00:07:42,316
Be quick to intervene and discipline the students making insults.

58
00:07:42,316 --> 00:07:48,713
This shows students of either gender that they will be supported.

59
00:07:48,713 --> 00:07:59,662
However it is important that both male and female students are given the same discipline for the same actions.

60
00:07:59,662 --> 00:08:08,555
These strategies will help teachers create a more equal classroom environment for their students.

61
00:08:08,555 --> 00:08:15,042
They will also help teachers effectively manage their classrooms.

62
00:08:15,042 --> 00:08:22,143
Remember: The best form of teaching is the fairest form of teaching!

63
00:08:22,143 --> 00:08:24,519
I’m Alice Bryant

64
00:08:24,519 --> 00:08:28,304
And I’m Phil Dierking